<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="121" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,981,1581,1645]" box="[151,981,1581,1608]" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,981,1581,1608]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="16" pageNumber="121" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,981,1581,1608]" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
Key to species of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dejean" authorityYear="1821" box="[492,611,1581,1608]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Dendarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[492,611,1581,1608]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">Dendarus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[687,742,1582,1608]" name="Iran" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">Iran</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[804,981,1581,1607]" name="Turkmenistan" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">Turkmenistan</collectingCountry>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,981,1581,1645]" box="[151,551,1618,1645]" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">(on females = not widened protarsi)</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="122" pageId="16" pageNumber="121" type="key">
<keyStep pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1687,2031]" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
<keyLead pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
1 Elytra with sparse (19–24 punctures in one row), strongly elongate (at least 1–3 striae), deeply impressed strial punctures (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1716,1740]" captionTargetBox="[153,1431,182,1689]" captionTargetId="figure-24@4.[151,1436,181,1692]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Dendarus spp., habitus.A–C = D. armeniacus; D–F = D. crenulatus; A, D = male, dorsally; B, E = male, ventrally; C, F = female, dorsally." pageId="16" pageNumber="121">Figs 2F</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[261,287,1716,1738]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1795,1819]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1768]" captionTargetId="figure-24@6.[151,1436,181,1771]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 3. Dendarus leonhardi. A = lectotype, male, dorsally; B = ditto, ventrally; C = labels of the lectotype; D = lectotype, male, laterally; E = male (non-type), dorsally; F = female (non-type), dorsally." pageId="16" pageNumber="121">3F</figureCitation>
)............................................................................................. 2
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1687,2031]" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
<keyLead pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
- Elytra with denser (27–40 punctures in one row), round (only several punctures in 1–2 rows can be elongate), not impressed or slightly impressed strial punctures (
<figureCitation box="[567,646,1775,1797]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1716,1740]" captionTargetBox="[153,1431,182,1689]" captionTargetId="figure-24@4.[151,1436,181,1692]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Dendarus spp., habitus.A–C = D. armeniacus; D–F = D. crenulatus; A, D = male, dorsally; B, E = male, ventrally; C, F = female, dorsally." pageId="16" pageNumber="121">Figs 2C</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[656,686,1775,1796]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1972,1996]" captionTargetBox="[155,1433,420,1941]" captionTargetId="figure-128@8.[151,1436,417,1949]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Dendarus spp., habitus. A–C = D. matthewsi sp. n.; D–F = D. simplex (Turkey, Hakkary Prov., Berçelan Yayla); A, D = male, dorsally; B, E = male, ventrally; C, F = female, dorsally." pageId="16" pageNumber="121">4C</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[696,725,1775,1797]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1047,1071]" captionTargetBox="[153,1432,239,1020]" captionTargetId="figure-41@10.[151,1436,237,1024]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 6. Dendarus transcaspicus, habitus. A = male, dorsally; B = male, ventrally; C = female, dorsally." pageId="16" pageNumber="121">6C</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[736,792,1775,1796]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1866,1890]" captionTargetBox="[154,1429,181,1835]" captionTargetId="figure-24@12.[151,1436,181,1842]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 8. D. vagabundus, habitus. A = male, dorsally (Iran, North Khorasan Province: Bojnurd); B = male, ventrally (Turkmenistan, Kopetdag); C = female, dorsally (Turkmenistan, Kopetdag); D = male, dorsally (Iran, Golestan Prov.: Khoshyeylag); F = female, dorsally (the same locality)." pageId="16" pageNumber="121">8C, E</figureCitation>
)................................................... 3
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1687,2031]" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
<keyLead pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
2 Body completely shiny. Puncturation of pronotum dense and coarse. Puncturation of elytral interstriae dense (
<figureCitation box="[1279,1350,1804,1826]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1716,1740]" captionTargetBox="[153,1431,182,1689]" captionTargetId="figure-24@4.[151,1436,181,1692]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Dendarus spp., habitus.A–C = D. armeniacus; D–F = D. crenulatus; A, D = male, dorsally; B, E = male, ventrally; C, F = female, dorsally." pageId="16" pageNumber="121">Fig. 2F</figureCitation>
)............................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Menetries" baseAuthorityYear="1832" box="[1306,1436,1833,1855]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Dendarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crenulatus">
<emphasis box="[1306,1436,1833,1855]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">D. crenulatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1687,2031]" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
<keyLead pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
- Head and pronotum shiny, elytra dull. Puncturation of pronotum fine and sparse. Puncturation of elytral interstriae very fine and sparse, poorly visible (
<figureCitation box="[444,515,1892,1914]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1795,1819]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1768]" captionTargetId="figure-24@6.[151,1436,181,1771]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 3. Dendarus leonhardi. A = lectotype, male, dorsally; B = ditto, ventrally; C = labels of the lectotype; D = lectotype, male, laterally; E = male (non-type), dorsally; F = female (non-type), dorsally." pageId="16" pageNumber="121">Fig. 3F</figureCitation>
)................................................................ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schuster" authorityYear="1940" box="[1314,1436,1892,1914]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Dendarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leonhardi">
<emphasis box="[1314,1436,1892,1914]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">D. leonhardi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1687,2031]" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
<keyLead pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
3 Puncturation of pronotum uneven: very fine and sparse, with round punctures at middle and sharply coarse and dense, elongate, often merged punctures on lateral sides (
<figureCitation box="[615,689,1951,1973]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1047,1071]" captionTargetBox="[153,1432,239,1020]" captionTargetId="figure-41@10.[151,1436,237,1024]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 6. Dendarus transcaspicus, habitus. A = male, dorsally; B = male, ventrally; C = female, dorsally." pageId="16" pageNumber="121">Fig. 6C</figureCitation>
)................................................ 
<taxonomicName box="[1275,1436,1951,1972]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Dendarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="transcaspicus">
<emphasis box="[1275,1436,1951,1972]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">D. transcaspicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1687,2031]" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
<keyLead pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
- Pronotum uniformly punctured with moderately dense or sparse round punctures, sometimes punctures on sides slightly denser, but not sharply (
<figureCitation box="[383,461,2009,2031]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1716,1740]" captionTargetBox="[153,1431,182,1689]" captionTargetId="figure-24@4.[151,1436,181,1692]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Dendarus spp., habitus.A–C = D. armeniacus; D–F = D. crenulatus; A, D = male, dorsally; B, E = male, ventrally; C, F = female, dorsally." pageId="16" pageNumber="121">Figs 2C</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[471,501,2010,2031]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1972,1996]" captionTargetBox="[155,1433,420,1941]" captionTargetId="figure-128@8.[151,1436,417,1949]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Dendarus spp., habitus. A–C = D. matthewsi sp. n.; D–F = D. simplex (Turkey, Hakkary Prov., Berçelan Yayla); A, D = male, dorsally; B, E = male, ventrally; C, F = female, dorsally." pageId="16" pageNumber="121">4C</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[511,567,2010,2031]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1866,1890]" captionTargetBox="[154,1429,181,1835]" captionTargetId="figure-24@12.[151,1436,181,1842]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 8. D. vagabundus, habitus. A = male, dorsally (Iran, North Khorasan Province: Bojnurd); B = male, ventrally (Turkmenistan, Kopetdag); C = female, dorsally (Turkmenistan, Kopetdag); D = male, dorsally (Iran, Golestan Prov.: Khoshyeylag); F = female, dorsally (the same locality)." pageId="16" pageNumber="121">8C, E</figureCitation>
)...................................................................... 4
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="17" pageNumber="122">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1436,151,290]" box="[151,1436,151,174]" pageId="17" pageNumber="122">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,151,174]" pageId="17" pageNumber="122">
4 Posterior angles of pronotum obtuse, not protruding (
<figureCitation box="[737,811,151,174]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1716,1740]" captionTargetBox="[153,1431,182,1689]" captionTargetId="figure-24@4.[151,1436,181,1692]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Dendarus spp., habitus.A–C = D. armeniacus; D–F = D. crenulatus; A, D = male, dorsally; B, E = male, ventrally; C, F = female, dorsally." pageId="17" pageNumber="122">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
)...................................... 
<taxonomicName authorityName="sensu G. Medvedev" authorityYear="1968" box="[1295,1436,152,173]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Dendarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="122" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="armeniacus">
<emphasis box="[1295,1436,152,173]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="122">D. armeniacus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1436,151,290]" box="[151,1436,181,203]" pageId="17" pageNumber="122">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,181,203]" pageId="17" pageNumber="122">
- Posterior angles of pronotum right or acute, weakly protruding (
<figureCitation box="[840,919,181,203]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1972,1996]" captionTargetBox="[155,1433,420,1941]" captionTargetId="figure-128@8.[151,1436,417,1949]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Dendarus spp., habitus. A–C = D. matthewsi sp. n.; D–F = D. simplex (Turkey, Hakkary Prov., Berçelan Yayla); A, D = male, dorsally; B, E = male, ventrally; C, F = female, dorsally." pageId="17" pageNumber="122">Figs 4C</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[929,985,181,202]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1866,1890]" captionTargetBox="[154,1429,181,1835]" captionTargetId="figure-24@12.[151,1436,181,1842]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 8. D. vagabundus, habitus. A = male, dorsally (Iran, North Khorasan Province: Bojnurd); B = male, ventrally (Turkmenistan, Kopetdag); C = female, dorsally (Turkmenistan, Kopetdag); D = male, dorsally (Iran, Golestan Prov.: Khoshyeylag); F = female, dorsally (the same locality)." pageId="17" pageNumber="122">8C, E</figureCitation>
)................................... 5
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="17" pageNumber="122">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1436,151,290]" box="[151,1436,210,232]" pageId="17" pageNumber="122">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,210,232]" pageId="17" pageNumber="122">
5 Elytral striae 1 and 2 close to each other, second interstria narrower than third one (
<figureCitation box="[1025,1129,210,232]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1866,1890]" captionTargetBox="[154,1429,181,1835]" captionTargetId="figure-24@12.[151,1436,181,1842]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 8. D. vagabundus, habitus. A = male, dorsally (Iran, North Khorasan Province: Bojnurd); B = male, ventrally (Turkmenistan, Kopetdag); C = female, dorsally (Turkmenistan, Kopetdag); D = male, dorsally (Iran, Golestan Prov.: Khoshyeylag); F = female, dorsally (the same locality)." pageId="17" pageNumber="122">Figs 8C, E</figureCitation>
)........... 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Reitter" authorityYear="1904" box="[1291,1436,210,232]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Dendarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="122" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vagabundus">
<emphasis box="[1291,1436,210,232]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="122">D. vagabundus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1436,151,290]" pageId="17" pageNumber="122">
<keyLead pageId="17" pageNumber="122">
- Elytral striae 1 and 2 not close to each other, second and third interstriae with the same width in middle (
<figureCitation box="[1229,1298,239,262]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1972,1996]" captionTargetBox="[155,1433,420,1941]" captionTargetId="figure-128@8.[151,1436,417,1949]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Dendarus spp., habitus. A–C = D. matthewsi sp. n.; D–F = D. simplex (Turkey, Hakkary Prov., Berçelan Yayla); A, D = male, dorsally; B, E = male, ventrally; C, F = female, dorsally." pageId="17" pageNumber="122">Fig 4C</figureCitation>
).............................................................................................. 
<taxonomicName authority="Nabozhenko &amp; Poggi, 2022" authorityName="Nabozhenko &amp; Poggi" authorityYear="2022" box="[1250,1376,269,290]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Dendarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="122" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="matthewsi" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[1250,1376,269,290]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="122">D. matthewsi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1382,1436,269,290]" pageId="17" pageNumber="122">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1382,1436,269,290]" pageId="17" pageNumber="122" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
</subSubSection>
